website_summaries.verdict: An excellent option for feeding voracious African clawed frogs and tadpoles of all kinds, as these little frog pellets are designed to make them feel full faster, which helps this jar of food to last longer than the average recipe.
pros: Anchovy fish meal, soybean meal, fish oil, wheat flour, and corn gluten meal are the first 5 ingredients
Preferred food for small amphibians and bottom-dwellers
cons: Tiny pellets may be lost in between pieces of gravel
Large aquatic frogs may prefer a bigger pellet

customer_reviews.title: The tadpoles love them
customer_reviews.text: We saved tadpoles from a puddle that was quickly evaporating and weren't sure what to feed them. After doing some research and read the reviews we chose to get this. Our tadpoles absolutely love these. We put the pellets in the same corner of their tank every time we feed them. We drop some pellets in every day and they go crazy for them. Our 7 year old loves watching them eat these.
customer_reviews.author: Dawn Keebals

customer_reviews.title: Good alternative nutrition for froggies.
customer_reviews.text: I use these not as a staple, but more as a supplement when I'm feeling lazy or out of frozen blood worms. They're little sinking pellets made especially for ADFs, and they can smell them in the water. They don't go nuts like for the worms, but it's nice to offer some variety in their diet. Edit: I'm upgrading my review after careful observation and going over the ingredients. My frogs usually find them because the #1 ingredient is anchovy meal. They're also packed with vitamins that bloodworms can't provide, so I've been using them more, and bloodworms maybe twice a week. With 50% protein, these are the most nutritious I've found that they like.
customer_reviews.author: Alice WakefieldTop Contributor: Gardening

customer_reviews.title: Ehh
customer_reviews.text: These are pretty messy and my dwarf frogs are pretty blind lol, I'll throw these in on days where I'm running late and don't have time to hand feed them I've seen them find a few and I'm sure they find more by sent after the lights go out but if you don't do weekly water changes your water will be polluted and kill your frogs, wouldn't recommend feeding these everyday unless you have fish that will do a little clean up.

customer_reviews.title: Nice small granules - don't seem to pollute the tank.
customer_reviews.text: The size of the granules is perfect for my african dwarf frogs. It does seem to take the frogs a long time to realize they are in the tank though, so I'm not sure they smell so strongly (never have that problem with live black worms). On the plus side it gives my shrimps a chance to eat them too - who seem to love them! The granules should be softened in a little water for a while before you attempt to feed, and I recommend a feeding dish because they could easily disappear in between gravel and never be found by the frogs.
